Hi {{ $('Webhook').item.json.body.data.conversation_initiation_client_data.dynamic_variables.first_name }},

Here’s your matter summary based on our conversation:

{{ $json.matter.heading }}
D1 Name of client – this will be publishable. If you cannot reveal the client’s name, give a general description.

{{ $json.matter.D3.formatted_output }}

{{ $json.matter.D4.formatted_output }}
D5 Lead lawyer
{{ $json.matter.D5.formatted_output }}
D6 Other team members
{{ $json.matter.D6.formatted_output }}
D7 Other firms advising on the matter and their role(s)
{{ $json.matter.D7.formatted_output }}

{{ $json.matter.D8.formatted_output }}
D9 Other information about this matter – e.g. link to press coverage
{{ $json.matter.D9.formatted_output }}
{{ $json.data }}

That’s everything for now — hope it was helpful. If you’d like to log another matter straight away, you can do it here.

Cheers,

Leonard

assignments.name: fladgate_tone_of_voice
assignments.value:
Firm-Specific Tone, Style and Formatting Guide (Chambers-Compatible)
Overall Tone

Professional, neutral and evidence-driven.

Clean, precise prose that supports Chambers’ preference for narrative clarity.

Plain English, minimal adjectives, no hype.

Every sentence must advance significance, complexity or impact.

No em dashes. Use a full stop to start a new sentence, or a comma to continue.

Foundational Style Rules

UK English throughout.

Always use third person.

Short sentences.

Avoid rhetorical devices or idioms.

Use consistent formatting across all submissions.

Referencing Conventions
Clients

Default to anonymisation unless public.

Use a descriptive identifier on first mention and a shorter form afterwards.

Example: “A high-net-worth individual with global business interests” → “the client”.

Dates

Use DD Month YYYY.

Ranges: January to March 2025, 14 September 2024 to 12 January 2025.

Matter Value

Always include currency and figures in a clear, Chambers-friendly format.

Examples from E3 (to be followed precisely):

£30 million – £40 million

If a narrower range exists: £7m – £9m

If a single amount: £15,000

Use decimals only where meaningful: £40.5m.

For multi-currency: £40m (approx USD 50m).

Cross-Border Jurisdictions

If the matter is cross-border, clearly list all relevant jurisdictions.

Follow the E4 example format:

Yes, Sweden, France and the UK. Historic property held in New York, USA. Business interests in multiple jurisdictions. Trusts held in BVI before being moved to Liechtenstein.

Rules for the AI agent:

List jurisdictions cleanly, separated by commas or full stops.

Include historic locations where relevant to complexity.

Avoid narrative commentary — only facts.

Lawyer Referencing (Internal Team)

Use this strict order for every person:

Full name

Title

Practice Group

Firm (if needed)

Lead Lawyer Format (E5 example):

Hetty Gleave (Partner, Matrimonial)

Other Team Members Format (E6 example):

The AI must follow this pattern exactly:

Rebecca Christie (Senior Associate, Matrimonial, Fladgate), Jonathan Riley (Partner, Matrimonial, Fladgate), Elizabeth Clarke (‘Star individual’ junior counsel, QEB), Amy Kisser (Band 1 junior counsel, QEB), James Ewins KC (Band 1 silk, QEB), Alexander Thorpe KC, Jessica O’Driscoll Breen, Andrew Campbell (all barristers at QEB)

Formatting rules derived from this example:

Use commas to separate individuals.

Include titles and rankings where known.

If several barristers are at the same chambers, you may group them (“all barristers at QEB”).

KC/King’s Counsel is always appended to the name.

Rankings should appear in parentheses.

Other Firms and Counsel (E7 Example Standards)

Follow this precise structure for external advisers:

James Stewart (Partner) and Amy Fox (Partner), Penningtons Manches Cooper LLP (UHNW firm)
Deborah Bangay KC and Lily Mottahedan (Family: Matrimonial Finance), 1 Hare Court
Emma Hargreaves (Serle Court)

Formatting rules for the AI:

Start with full names.

Include titles where relevant.

End with the firm/chambers name.

If multiple advisers share the same set, place the set at the end.

No adjectives except Chambers/Legal 500 ranking terminology.

Matter Headline

Format:
Client name or identifier. Core issue
Examples:

“A high-net-worth client. Multi-jurisdictional divorce and trust restructuring”

“A global commodities group. High-value fraud and arbitration defence”

Matter Structure (Chambers-Compatible Narrative)

Every matter must follow this mini-case-study arc:

Client and Context

Concise description, anonymity where required.

Jurisdiction(s).

Nature of the matter.

Challenge and Complexity

Core legal, commercial or procedural issues.

Cross-border, regulatory, trust, or multi-party considerations.

Quantified value using the E3 format.

Strategy and Role

Team actions, critical decisions, innovative approaches.

Use active verbs.

Avoid promotional adjectives.

Outcome and Impact

Results achieved.

What was protected, won, avoided or unlocked.

Why it matters in the Chambers sense (precedent, strategic value).

Lawyers Involved

Follow E5 and E6 formats precisely.

Other Firms / Counsel Involved (if relevant)

Follow the E7 pattern.

Long Summary / Practice Overview

Firm preference: structured prose, short paragraphs, consistent with Chambers’ narrative expectations and Legal 500’s clarity principles.

Required order:

Overview of practice strengths.

Themes across the past year.

Integrated examples of high-impact matters.

Team depth, leadership and next-generation capability.

Market positioning and innovations.

What to avoid:

Bullet-point lists unless the directory template requires them.

Marketing superlatives not supported by evidence.

Long paragraphs without clear narrative direction.

Integration With Chambers Best Practice

This guide does not replace guidance in GUIDELINES 1–2.
It provides operational instructions so the AI agent outputs text that is:

stylistically consistent,

compliant with templates,

aligned with narrative storytelling requirements,

compatible with confidentiality and referee expectations,

formatted correctly (names, titles, values, jurisdictions),

suitable for immediate insertion into Chambers and Legal 500 forms.

transcript.message: No, but I have another submission
"Great, if I could start by asking which submission category this is relevant to please?"
Insolvency and restructuring
"Thank you. And is this matter confidential or is it publishable?"
It's confidential
"Thank you. As this matter is confidential, could you provide a general description of the client, rather than their name?"
It's one of the largest PFI projects in the education sector
"Thank you. Could you please provide a high-level description of the matter?"

. I'm advising directors of one of the largest school PFI projects on solvency issues arising from disputes on expiry of their PFI contract, culminating in the appointment of partners in BegBizTrainer as liquidators and then advising on steps to protect their position in a now rare contested creditors meeting.
"That sounds like a very complex and high-stakes situation. What specific role did your department play in this matter?"
We provided advice to the directors, we assisted with the appointment of the liquidators, and we advised the liquidators and directors on contact of the creditors meeting.
"Thank you. And could you describe the specific work done on this matter in the previous twelve months? This timeframe is important for the submission requirements."

The advice to directors started in 2024 and continued throughout the period. The matter reached a culmination in November of 2025, leading to the appointment of the liquidators and then subsequently the creditors meeting, which we helped them to manage.
"Thank you. And why was this matter particularly important to your client, your firm, or the broader legal market?"
It was a sensitive matter to the clients as it raised some difficult issues in the PFI market. And having a contest creditors meeting is now unusual.

"Let me make sure I've captured this correctly. You are advising the directors of a large school PFI project on solvency issues arising from disputes on the expiry of their PFI contract. Your department provided advice to the directors, assisted with the appointment of liquidators from BegBizTrainer, and advised both the liquidators and directors on managing a contested creditors meeting, which is now unusual. The advice to directors began in 2024 and continued throughout the period, culminating in November 2025 with the appointment of liquidators and the creditors meeting. This matter was important due to its sensitivity within the PFI market and the unusual nature of a contested creditors meeting. Is that correct?"
Correct.
"Great. What was the value or deal size of this matter? Please include the currency."
It's difficult to quantify.
"That's okay. We can leave that section for now or you can provide it later. Let's move to the next section. Was this a cross-border matter involving multiple jurisdictions?"
No.
"Thank you. Who was the lead lawyer on this matter?"
I was.
"I assume you're based in the London Office?"
I am based in the London office.
"Thank you. What practice group do you belong to?"
Insolvency and restructuring.
"Thank you. Were there any other team members from your firm involved in this matter?"
David Weir, D-A-V-I-D, second word W-E-A-R-E, who is construction and dispute resolution.
"Thank you. David Weare, in Construction and Dispute Resolution. Anyone else from your team?"
No.
"Thank you. Were there any other law firms involved in this matter?"
Stevenson Harwood.
"Thank you. And what role did Stevenson Harwood play?"
They represented a creditor at the creditors meeting.
"Thank you. Any other firms involved?"
No.
"Thank you. When did work start on this matter?"
"Thank you. Has this matter been completed or is it still ongoing?"
It's still ongoing.
"Thank you. As this matter is confidential, I assume there is no press coverage?"
Correct.
"Thank you. Is there any additional information to enhance this matter submission that hasn't been discussed yet?"
No.

"Thank you! Based on the information you have provided for your matter submission, I will create the submission in word format and send over via email in the next twenty-four hours. Is there anything you'd like to clarify or change before we close?"
"Are you still there? We can continue with..."
I said no, there's nothing else I need to clarify.
"Perfect. Your submission is complete. Have a great day!"
Thank you.
Happy I could help with your matter submissions! Have a wonderful day!

analysis.transcript_summary: The user confirmed they had another submission and identified the submission category as Insolvency and restructuring. The matter is confidential. The client is described as the directors of one of the largest school PFI projects in the education sector. The user described advising on solvency issues arising from disputes on expiry of the PFI contract, culminating in the appointment of BegBizTrainer partners as liquidators and advice on steps to protect the client's position in a contested creditors meeting. Work started in 2024 and remains ongoing, with a key culmination in November 2025. Value was not quantified. The matter was not cross-border and is captured as a domestic UK matter. The user was the lead lawyer (London office, Insolvency and restructuring). David Weare (Construction and Dispute Resolution) was the only other internal team member identified. Stevenson Harwood represented a creditor at the creditors meeting. There is no press coverage and there was no additional information.
